  <section1 id="sIP">
	<secTitle>Basic, Single-Clause Sentences</secTitle>
	<p>
	  <content>This section covers intransitive, copular, transitive, ditransitive and passive sentences in their basic surface word order (i.e. not changed by focus, topic, interrogative, or negation constructions).  As noted in section </content>
	  <sectionRef sec="sIntro"/>
	  <content>,  the typology of </content>
	  <langName/>
	  <content> is </content>
	  <case element="typology" attr="wordOrder">
		<caseText value="SVO">SVO, so the basic word order is the subject, then any auxiliary elements, then the verb phrase which consists of the verb in initial position and any complements following it.</caseText>
		<caseText value="SOV">SOV, so the basic word order is the subject, then the verb phrase which consists of the verb in final position with any complements preceding it, then any auxiliary elements.</caseText>
		<caseText value="VSO">VSO, so the basic word order is the verb in initial position, then the subject, then any complements.</caseText>
		<caseText value="VOS">VOS, so the basic word order is the verb phrase which consists of the verb in initial position and any complements following it, then any auxiliary elements, then the subject.</caseText>
		<caseText value="OVS">OVS, so the basic word order is the verb phrase which consists of the verb in final position with any complements preceding it, then any auxiliary elements, then the subject.</caseText>
		<caseText value="OSV">OSV, so the basic word order is any verbal complements first, then the subject, then the verb in final position.</caseText>
	  </case>
	  <content> </content>
	  <text show="swVSOorOSV">
		<content>The order with any auxiliaries present will be discussed in section </content>
		<sectionRef sec="sIPAux"/>
		<content>.</content>
	  </text>
	  <content> </content>
	</p>
	<p>
	  <content>Before discussing each of the sentence types in turn, general issues of inflection and agreement features, pro-drop, and auxiliaries will be covered.</content>
	</p>
