	<section2 id="sIPAux">
	  <secTitle>Auxiliaries</secTitle>
	  <p>
		<content>Some languages have auxiliary elements that are separate words, and some can have more than one auxiliary element before the main verb.  Examples for English transitive single-clause sentences include: </content>
		<langData>The boy will hit the ball</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>The boy might have hit the ball</langData>
		<content> and </content>
		<langData>The boy might have been hitting the ball</langData>
		<content>.</content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content> </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> </content>
		<case element="ip" attr="aux">
		  <caseText value="no">does not have any</caseText>
		  <caseText value="yes">has some</caseText>
		</case>
		<content> auxiliaries which are written as separate words.  </content>
		<text show="swIPAuxYes">
		  <content>Examples of auxiliaries that are like the English auxiliaries include:</content>
		</text>
		<content> </content>
	  </p>
	  <example show="swIPAuxYes">
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/auxExample"/>
	  </example>
	  <p>
		<content>The nonfinite word </content>
		<langData>to</langData>
		<content> used in English embedded clauses also acts as an auxiliary in that it fills the same position and can occur before other auxiliaries.  For example, </content>
		<langData>The boy would like to have hit the ball</langData>
		<content>.  Nonfinite examples from </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> are given here, though they may not include a nonfinite auxiliary element:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example>
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/auxNonfiniteExample"/>
	  </example>
	  <p show="swIPAuxYes">
		<content>Some languages have other words that act like auxiliaries, such as motion auxiliaries or loan markers, which are written </content>
		<text show="swVInitial">
		  <content>before</content>
		</text>
		<content> </content>
		<text show="swVFinal">
		  <content>after</content>
		</text>
		<content> the verb and share the same subject and complements.  Examples of these other kinds of auxiliaries, if used in </content>
		<langName/>
		<content>, are given below:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example show="swIPAuxYes">
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/auxOtherExample"/>
	  </example>
	  <p show="swIPAuxYes">
		<content>An auxiliary is </content>
		<case element="ip" attr="auxRequired">
		  <caseText value="no">optional</caseText>
		  <caseText value="no">required</caseText>
		</case>
		<content> and  </content>
		<case element="ip" attr="auxMany">
		  <caseText value="no">only one is possible</caseText>
		  <caseText value="yes">more than one may occur</caseText>
		</case>
		<content> in a single clause. </content>
		<text show="swIPAuxOrderVSO">
		  <content>After an auxiliary, the normal VSO order </content>
		  <case element="ip" attr="auxOrder">
			<caseText value="yes">is maintained.  The order is Aux V S O.</caseText>
			<caseText value="no">may change so the subject appears directly after the auxiliary and before the verb.  The order in these clauses is Aux S V O.</caseText>
		  </case>
		  <content> </content>
		</text>
		<content> </content>
		<text show="swIPAuxOrderOSV">
		  <content>Before an auxiliary, the normal OSV order </content>
		  <case element="ip" attr="auxOrder">
			<caseText value="yes">is maintained.  The order is O S V Aux.</caseText>
			<caseText value="no">may change so the subject appears directly after the verb and before the auxiliary.  The order in these clauses is O V S Aux.</caseText>
		  </case>
		  <content> </content>
		</text>
		<content> </content>
	  </p>
	</section2>
	<section2 id="sIPMotion">
	  <secTitle>Intransitives and Motion Verbs</secTitle>
	  <p>
		<content>Simple intransitives do not have any complements after the verb, such as </content>
		<langData>The girl swims</langData>
		<content>.  Motion verbs include a location in the form of either a PP or adverb.  English examples of motion verbs include </content>
		<langData>The girl ran around the track</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>My mother went to the store</langData>
		<content> and </content>
		<langData>My teacher came here</langData>
		<content>.</content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content>Examples of simple intransitive in </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> include:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example>
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/intransExample"/>
	  </example>
	  <p>
		<content> </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> examples with motion verbs include:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example>
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/motionExample"/>
	  </example>
	</section2>
	<section2 id="sIPCop">
	  <secTitle>Copular Constructions</secTitle>
	  <p>
		<content>Copular sentences can have an adjective, PP, or nominal phrase following the copular verb.  Some languages do not require a copular verb or auxiliary to be present.  English examples include </content>
		<langData>The girl is pretty</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>She seems nice</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>The girl is in charge</langData>
		<content> and </content>
		<langData>He is the leader</langData>
		<content>.</content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content>In </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> copular sentences, </content>
		<case element="ip" attr="copular">
		  <caseText value="yes">an overt copular verb is required.</caseText>
		  <caseText value="noAux">a copular verb is not necessary, but an auxiliary is required.</caseText>
		  <caseText value="noNeither">neither an overt copular verb nor an auxiliary is required.</caseText>
		</case>
		<content> </content>
		<text show="swIPCopVerbNoNeither">
		  <content>There is </content>
		  <case element="ip" attr="copularAffix">
			<caseText value="no">not any copular affix on the predicate nominal or predicate adjective either.</caseText>
			<caseText value="yes">a copular affix on the predicate nominal or predicate adjective, however.</caseText>
		  </case>
		  <content> </content>
		</text>
		<content> </content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content>Examples of copular sentences in </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> include:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example>
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/copularExample"/>
	  </example>
	</section2>
	<section2 id="sIPTrans">
	  <secTitle>Transitives and Ditransitives</secTitle>
	  <p>
		<content>Examples of English transitive single-clause sentences include </content>
		<langData>The batter will hit the ball</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>My baby wants that toy</langData>
		<content> and </content>
		<langData>The dog might have buried his bone</langData>
		<content>.</content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content> </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> examples of transitive sentences include:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example>
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/example"/>
	  </example>
	  <p>
		<content>Ditransitives can have the second object expressed as a PP or as a nominal phrase (DP).  Some languages, like English, allow both types via Dative Movement, as in </content>
		<langData>The girl gave the gift to her mother</langData>
		<content> and </content>
		<langData>The girl gave her mother the gift</langData>
		<content>.</content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content>In </content>
		<langName/>
		<content>, the second object in a ditransitive </content>
		<case element="ip" attr="diCat">
		  <caseText value="pp">is always a PP></caseText>
		  <caseText value="dp">is always a nominal phrase.></caseText>
		  <caseText value="both">can be either a PP or a nominal phrase.></caseText>
		</case>
		<content>  Examples of ditransitive sentences in </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> include:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example>
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/diExample"/>
	  </example>
	</section2>
	<section2 id="sIPPassive">
	  <secTitle>Passives</secTitle>
	  <p>
		<content>Most languages also have passive sentences, where the Theme or Patient fills the subject position.  The Agent may be optionally expressed in some languages, but not allowed at all in others.  If expressed, it may take the form of a PP (as in English with the particular preposition </content>
		<langData>by</langData>
		<content>) or a nominal phrase (DP), depending on the language.  In addition, a particular auxiliary may be required in passives (a form of </content>
		<langData>be</langData>
		<content> in English).  English examples with and without an agent phrase, including some showing interaction with multiple auxiliaries are:</content>
		<langData>The glass was broken</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>The glass was broken by the child</langData>
		<content>, </content>
		<langData>The ball might have been hit</langData>
		<content> and </content>
		<langData>The ball might have been hit by the boy</langData>
		<content>.</content>
	  </p>
	  <p>
		<content> </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> </content>
		<case element="ip" attr="passive">
		  <caseText value="no">does not have any passives.</caseText>
		  <caseText value="yes">has passives</caseText>
		</case>
		<content> </content>
		<text show="swIPPassiveYes">
		  <content> in which the Agent </content>
		  <case element="ip" attr="passiveAgent">
			<caseText value="no">may not be expressed.</caseText>
			<caseText value="yes">may be expressed</caseText>
		  </case>
		  <content> </content>
		  <text show="swIPPassiveAgentYes">
			<content> as a </content>
			<case element="ip" attr="passiveAgentCat">
			  <caseText value="pp">PP.</caseText>
			  <caseText value="dp">nominal phrase.</caseText>
			</case>
			<content> </content>
		  </text>
		  <content>  A particular auxiliary </content>
		  <case element="ip" attr="passiveAux">
			<caseText value="no">is not</caseText>
			<caseText value="no">is</caseText>
		  </case>
		  <content> required in passive sentences.</content>
		</text>
		<content> </content>
	  </p>
	  <p show="swIPPassiveYes">
		<content>Examples of passive sentences in </content>
		<langName/>
		<content> include:</content>
	  </p>
	  <example show="swIPPassiveYes">
		<interlinear exampleLoc="ip/passiveExample"/>
	  </example>
	</section2>
